// Shinto kami — the 12 canonical deities of the Japanese pantheon — SEO funnel.
// /gab44/shinto-kami (index) + /gab44/shinto-kami/{slug}.
//
// The ninth great pantheon on gab44 after Olympians, Norse, Hindu Devas,
// Egyptian, Celtic, Orishas, Mesopotamian, and Aztec. The FIRST East Asian
// pantheon on the site — closing the structural geographic gap of having
// covered Europe (Greek, Norse, Celtic), Africa (Egyptian, Orisha),
// Mesopotamia, the Indian subcontinent (Hindu), and the pre-Columbian
// Americas (Aztec) without any presence from East Asia. Also the only
// pantheon on gab44 that is *still the state-recognised national-cultic
// system of a contemporary G7 country* (Shinto kami are enshrined in
// roughly 80,000 active shrines across Japan as of 2026, ~3% of the
// population identifies as Shintoist but ~70% participates in at least
// one annual Shinto ritual — the gap between exclusive-identification
// and ritual-participation is the most-distinctive sociological fact
// about Shinto and makes it incomparable to the other pantheons here).
//
// Three families × 4 kami:
//  - Celestial / Amatsukami (the kami of Takamagahara, the High Plain
//    of Heaven): Amaterasu the sun-goddess + Susanoo the storm-brother
//    + Tsukuyomi the moon-brother + Ame-no-Uzume the dawn-dancer who
//    lured Amaterasu out of the rock-cave with her ecstatic dance.
//  - Earthly / Kunitsukami (the kami of the land, the indigenous
//    pre-descent powers that ruled Japan before the heavenly grandson
//    descended): Ōkuninushi the Izumo great-land-lord who built the
//    country and then ceded it + Inari the rice-and-fox kami of 1/3
//    of all Japanese shrines + Sarutahiko the great earthly-kami who
//    met the heavenly descent at the eight-crossroads + Watatsumi
//    the dragon-king of the sea.
//  - Syncretic & Folk / Shinbutsu (the kami of the Buddhist-Shinto
//    synthesis and the folk-protective register): Hachiman the war-
//    kami and bodhisattva-status patron of the Minamoto samurai +
//    Benzaiten the water-music-eloquence goddess (Saraswati arrived
//    via the Sutra of Golden Light) + Ebisu the laughing fisherman-
//    luck-god of merchants and the Seven Lucky Gods + Konohana-no-
//    Sakuya-hime the cherry-blossom-and-Mount-Fuji goddess of
//    ephemeral beauty.
//
// Source-honest from the *Kojiki* (Records of Ancient Matters, 712 CE,
// compiled by Ō no Yasumaro from the recitations of Hieda no Are at
// the command of Empress Genmei — the oldest extant Japanese text
// and the source of the Amaterasu-Susanoo cycle, the rock-cave
// myth, the Izumo cycle, and the descent of Ninigi), the *Nihon
// Shoki* / *Nihongi* (Chronicles of Japan, 720 CE — the same myths
// in more Sinified literary form, with multiple variant readings
// preserved), the *Engishiki* (Procedures of the Engi Era, 927 CE,
// 50 books — the indispensable record of which 2,861 shrines were
// state-recognized at the early-Heian zenith), the *Fudoki* (the
// regional gazetteers c. 713-733 CE — Izumo Fudoki, Harima Fudoki,
// Hitachi Fudoki, Hizen Fudoki, Bungo Fudoki — preserving local
// kami unmentioned in the Kojiki), the *Norito* (the great ancient
// ritual prayers preserved in Engishiki Book 8), the *Manyōshū*
// (the c. 759 CE poetry anthology with kami-invocations), the
// *Kogo Shūi* (807 CE Imbe Hironari's complementary mythological
// record), the *Sendai Kuji Hongi* (c. 9th-c. Mononobe-clan
// counter-tradition), Motoori Norinaga's *Kojiki-den* (1764-1798 —
// the 44-volume Kokugaku-school commentary that re-canonized the
// Kojiki and is the source of every modern "pure Shinto" reading
// of the text), Hirata Atsutane's nativist theology (c. 1820s);
// modern scholarship: Carmen Blacker *The Catalpa Bow* (Allen &
// Unwin 1975 — the canonical English-language study of Japanese
// shamanism), Helen Hardacre *Shinto: A History* (Oxford 2017 — the
// magisterial single-volume history), Mark Teeuwen & Bernhard
// Scheid eds. *Shinto in History* (Curzon 2003), John Breen & Mark
// Teeuwen *A New History of Shinto* (Wiley 2010), Allan Grapard
// *The Protocol of the Gods: A Study of the Kasuga Cult in
// Japanese History* (California 1992 — the standard work on
// shinbutsu-shūgō Buddhist-Shinto synthesis), Stuart Picken
// *Essentials of Shinto* (Greenwood 1994) and *Sourcebook in
// Shinto* (Greenwood 2004), Ian Reader *Religion in Contemporary
// Japan* (Macmillan 1991), Brian Bocking *A Popular Dictionary of
// Shinto* (Curzon 1996), Sokyo Ono *Shinto: The Kami Way*
// (Tuttle 1962 — the postwar Jinja Honchō standard introduction),
// Inoue Nobutaka et al. *Shinto: A Short History* (RoutledgeCurzon
// 2003 — translation of Kokugakuin University consensus account),
// Mark Teeuwen & Fabio Rambelli eds. *Buddhas and Kami in Japan:
// Honji Suijaku as a Combinatory Paradigm* (RoutledgeCurzon 2003).
//
// Shadow-honest: the Meiji-Restoration State Shinto period 1868-1945
// and the *Shinbutsu-bunri* (separation of kami and buddhas) edicts
// of 1868 that *deliberately destroyed* the c. 1,200-year-old
// Buddhist-Shinto honji-suijaku synthesis (thousands of Buddhist
// statues smashed, jingūji shrine-temple complexes split, Buddhist
// monks defrocked from kami-shrines they had served for centuries —
// the Haibutsu-kishaku "abolish the Buddha, kill Śākyamuni" violence
// of 1868-1872); the *invention of "State Shinto"* (Kokka Shintō)
// as a non-religion "national-ritual" that all Japanese were
// constitutionally required to participate in regardless of personal
// religion (the 1889 Meiji Constitution + the 1890 Imperial Rescript
// on Education + the 1900 Bureau of Shrines administrative system);
// the deification of the Meiji Emperor in 1912 and the use of the
// imperial-divinity-myth (the descent of Ninigi from Amaterasu as
// the literal genealogical origin of the imperial house) to justify
// 1894-1945 imperial expansion in Korea, Taiwan, Manchuria, China,
// Southeast Asia, and the Pacific; the *Yasukuni Shrine* (founded
// 1869) controversy in which 2,466,532 Japanese war-dead are
// enshrined as kami — including, since 1978, 14 Class-A war
// criminals from the Tokyo War Crimes Tribunal — and which is
// still the focus of perennial diplomatic crises with South Korea
// and China when Japanese Prime Ministers visit; the December 1945
// Shinto Directive of the Allied Occupation that formally abolished
// State Shinto, and Emperor Shōwa (Hirohito)'s 1 January 1946
// *Ningen Sengen* "Humanity Declaration" formally renouncing the
// imperial-divinity claim; the postwar 1946 Constitution Article 20
// separation of state and religion that left the imperial-Shinto-
// rituals (Daijōsai great-thanksgiving-enthronement, Niinamesai
// new-rice-festival) in a still-unresolved gray zone; the 1965-66
// Tsu City Jichinsai groundbreaking-ceremony Supreme Court case;
// the Heisei-and-Reiwa-era *Jinja Honchō* (the postwar
// Association of Shinto Shrines) and its conservative-political
// positions (Nippon Kaigi affiliation, opposition to female
// imperial succession, support for constitutional revision); the
// 19th-c. and contemporary Western New-Age reduction of Shinto to
// "Japanese nature-religion" or "the original earth-based animism"
// (popularised by Lafcadio Hearn in *Glimpses of Unfamiliar
// Japan* 1894 and *Japan: An Attempt at Interpretation* 1904
// and continued through 1980s Joseph-Campbell-tradition
// comparative-religion that flattened the specifically
// Japanese-historical-political content of Shinto into a generic
// "honoring of nature spirits"); the anime-and-tourist
// commodification of *kitsune* (Inari's fox-messengers) into
// generic "Japanese spirit foxes" detached from the Inari-rice-
// economy religious context; the post-Studio-Ghibli (especially
// *Spirited Away* 2001) Western popular-culture reading of Shinto
// kami as "Japanese Pokémon" or "anime spirits"; the 2020 Tokyo
// Olympics opening-ceremony Shinto-purification-ritual
// controversy and the ongoing debate about whether the Daijōsai
// imperial-enthronement-ritual (last performed November 2019 for
// Emperor Naruhito) constitutes a religious or a cultural-state
// rite under Article 20; the ongoing *yorishiro* (kami-vessel)
// tourist-photography that has begun to commercially erode the
// boundary between participant-and-observer in shrine spaces.

