    one_liner: 'The sun-goddess. The Great August Kami who Shines from Heaven. The ancestress of the Japanese imperial house (in unbroken genealogical line per the Kojiki, the descent from her grandson Ninigi through the legendary first emperor Jimmu c. 660 BCE through Emperor Naruhito today as the 126th). The withdrawer into the Ama-no-Iwato rock-cave when Susanoo defecated in her sacred weaving-hall — and the lured-back-out by Ame-no-Uzume\'s ecstatic dance, the foundational myth of Japanese performing arts. The giver of the three Imperial Regalia: the Yata-no-Kagami mirror (still housed at Ise), the Yasakani-no-Magatama jewel (Imperial Palace Tokyo), the Kusanagi-no-Tsurugi sword (Atsuta Jingū Nagoya). The kami whose Naikū at Ise has been rebuilt every 20 years for 1,300 years in the Shikinen Sengū continuity.',
    meaning: 'Amaterasu (天照, "shining-from-heaven") is the *cosmic-sun* of the Japanese pantheon — and uniquely among great-world-pantheons, the sun-deity is *feminine* (the only major comparable feminine-sun-deity is the Norse Sól, and the only major comparable solar-ancestress-of-the-ruling-line is the Egyptian Re-of-Pharaoh; Amaterasu combines both). She is born from Izanagi\'s purification-washing of his *left eye* at Ahagihara in southern Kyushu after his return from Yomi the land-of-the-dead — Susanoo from the *nose* and Tsukuyomi from the *right eye* are her brothers. She rules Takamagahara (the High Plain of Heaven). The central narrative is the *Iwato-gakure* (the rock-cave withdrawal): Susanoo, in storm-rage, flays a piebald horse and throws it backwards through the roof of her sacred weaving-hall (the Kojiki preserves the version where one of her weaving-women is killed by the falling shuttle); Amaterasu in grief and rage withdraws into the Ama-no-Iwato (the heavenly rock-cave), and the world goes dark. The eight-million kami gather at the Ame-no-Yasu-no-Kawara (the heavenly-tranquil-river-bed) to plan; Ame-no-Uzume (the dawn-dancer) performs an ecstatic, half-naked, foot-stamping dance on an overturned tub; the kami laugh; Amaterasu, curious about the laughter, opens the cave-door a crack; Tajikara-o (the strong-armed kami) pulls her out; the cave is sealed with a sacred rope (the origin of the *shimenawa* boundary-marker on every shrine). She then sends her grandson Ninigi-no-Mikoto down from heaven with the three Imperial Regalia and the command to rule the land, founding the imperial line. Her central shrine is the *Ise Jingū Naikū* (the Inner Shrine, Mie Prefecture), which has been rebuilt-exactly every twenty years since 690 CE in the *Shikinen Sengū* ritual-renewal (the next rebuilding is 2033) — the longest unbroken architectural-ritual continuity in world religious history. The kami-body of Amaterasu at Ise is the *Yata-no-Kagami* (the mirror), which is *never seen* — even the high-priestess (the Saishu, traditionally an imperial princess) approaches it veiled. The Amaterasu-register is the *cosmic-feminine-solar*, the *imperial-ancestral*, the *withdrawn-and-coaxed-back*, the *seen-only-through-the-veil*.',
    iconography: 'Almost never anthropomorphically depicted in classical Shinto art (this is itself iconographically significant — the *yorishiro* mirror is the kami-body, and direct representation was traditionally avoided). When depicted (medieval picture-scrolls, modern manga): a regal court-woman with the *jewel-and-mirror* held at the chest, often emerging from a rock-cave with a halo of sun-rays. In Buddhist *honji-suijaku* readings (medieval period through 1868), she is identified with *Mahāvairocana Buddha* (Dainichi Nyorai, the cosmic-sun-Buddha of the Shingon and Tendai schools) — this identification produced a vast medieval Mikkyō-Shintō iconographic synthesis (the *Ryōbu Mandala of the Two Realms* mapped onto the Ise inner and outer shrines), almost entirely destroyed in the 1868 Shinbutsu-bunri edicts. Colors: white (the imperial register, the Ise-shrine register), gold (the solar register), polished-bronze-mirror. Sacred objects: the *Yata-no-Kagami* mirror, the *shimenawa* sacred rope (commemorating the cave-sealing), the *mikoshi* portable-shrine. Sacred sites: Ise Jingū Naikū (the central shrine — visited by ~8 million pilgrims annually); Amanoiwato Jinja (in Takachiho, Miyazaki — the alleged cave-site, in the volcanic Kyushu cosmography of the Tenson kōrin heavenly-descent); Amaterasu shrines in every prefecture (the *jingū* honorific is reserved for shrines of imperial-rank, of which Amaterasu has the most).',
