    the_shadow: 'Amaterasu has been *politically weaponized into near-unrecoverable distortion* by the 1868-1945 State Shinto period. The Meiji oligarchs, in the Shinbutsu-bunri edicts of 1868, deliberately destroyed the c. 1,200-year-old Buddhist-Shinto honji-suijaku synthesis (in which Amaterasu had been identified with Mahāvairocana Buddha and her shrine network had been integrated with Buddhist temples), creating a "pure Shinto" (Kokka Shintō, State Shinto) that was administratively-defined as "not a religion" (so it could be made universally compulsory under the 1889 Constitution\'s nominal religious-freedom clause). The Meiji Emperor was declared a *living kami* in direct descent from Amaterasu (the 1889 Constitution Article 3: "The Emperor is sacred and inviolable"), and the Amaterasu-Ninigi-Jimmu genealogical line was made the *literal historical-foundational claim* of the Japanese state used to justify expansion in Korea 1910, Taiwan 1895, Manchuria 1931, China 1937, and the Pacific War 1941-45. The Ise Grand Shrine was elevated to the head of a national shrine-ranking system (the *shakaku* of 1871), and visiting Ise was made an obligation for emperor, ministers, and schoolchildren. After surrender, the December 1945 Shinto Directive of the Allied Occupation formally abolished State Shinto, and Emperor Shōwa\'s 1 January 1946 *Ningen Sengen* "Humanity Declaration" formally renounced the imperial-divinity-claim — but the formal Shinto-imperial-rituals (the once-in-a-reign Daijōsai, the annual Niinamesai, the Shikinen Sengū at Ise, performed November 2013 and scheduled 2033) continue under unresolved Article-20 separation-of-church-and-state ambiguity. The contemporary Jinja Honchō (the Association of Shinto Shrines, postwar-1946 federation of ~80,000 shrines) holds politically-conservative positions (Nippon Kaigi affiliation, opposition to female imperial succession, support for constitutional revision, public-funding of imperial-Shinto-rituals) that critics argue reproduce State-Shinto patterns. The further shadow: the Western New-Age reduction of Amaterasu to "Japanese sun-goddess generic" (popular in 1980s-2010s neo-Pagan feminist reclamations of "goddess pantheons of the world") flattens the specifically Japanese-imperial-ancestral content into a sun-goddess archetype that the actual Amaterasu-cult would not recognize. The deepest shadow: the use of Amaterasu in 21st-century *uyoku-dantai* (Japanese ultranationalist) propaganda continues, and any non-Japanese practitioner who invokes Amaterasu without naming this political shadow risks reproducing it.',
